        "title": "6c. `fetch_*` async functions ã untested pagination/dedup loops (real bug-prone logic)",
        "content": "\nThe recurring pattern across `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver`, `fetch_eightfold`, `fetch_apple`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_bytedance`, `fetch_phenom`, `fetch_google`: paginate until a page returns *no fresh* IDs, tracking a `seen` set. None of these loops are tested for:\n- Stopping correctly when a page returns only already-seen IDs (not just empty).\n- Respecting `max_pages` as a hard cap even if the server keeps returning fresh data forever (protects against a server bug causing infinite pagination).\n- `fetch_workday`'s different-shaped stop condition (`offset >= total or offset > 5000`).\n- `fetch_ashby`'s 200ã404 branching (posting-api available vs disabled-fallback-to-HTML) and the \"neither works\" `RuntimeError`.\n- `fetch_meta`'s token-scraping regexes and the `\"for (;;);\"` XSSI-prefix strip, plus the `errors` key ã `RuntimeError` path (this is the doc_id-rotation failure mode the module docstring specifically warns about).\n\n```python\n",
