        "title": "Priority ranking if coverage is added incrementally",
        "content": "1. **`models.py` + `filters.py`** ã pure functions, no mocking needed, highest ROI, catches dedup/filter-matching bugs (the app's actual correctness contract).\n2. **`store.py`** ã the dedup source of truth; a bug here silently re-notifies or silently drops jobs, and it's the one module with real state/concurrency semantics (`next_seq`'s `BEGIN IMMEDIATE`) worth locking down.\n3. **`fetchers.py` `parse_*` functions** ã cheapest to test (pure, no I/O) and the most frequently-breaking code in this repo per your own memory notes (Meta's doc_id rotation, ByteDance schema strictness, Microsoft's URL migration) ã regression tests here would have caught prior incidents you've already hit.\n4. **`agent.py` `cmd_db_new` truncation/watermark logic** ã subtle enough that a bug would silently corrupt what the scan pipeline sees, worth locking down given [[jobsquare-parallel-worker-collisions]] already shows this pipeline has had state-corruption issues.\n5. **`notify.py` + `fetch_*` async functions** ã need `respx`/env mocking, more setup cost, but protect against silent notification loss and pagination infinite-loops respectively.\n6. **`agent.py` PDF rendering / Chrome subprocess path** ã lowest priority; requires a real browser, best covered by 1-2 integration tests gated behind a Chrome-available check rather than exhaustive unit tests.",
